**Link Count**
--> A link count in linux shows how many names point to the same file.
--> link count of a file tells the total no of links a file has.

-types of links:
1. Hard Link
2. Soft Link

1. Hard link: (different names for same file)
i] These links have actual file contents.
syntax:
       ln <original-file> <link_name>
    eg:
       ln  demo  hard-link 
ii] hard link file is assigned the same inode value as the original file so they refer same physical location
*inode value*:
-An inode no is unique identification number assigened to every file in linux file system.
-an inode stores metadata about a file such as file type, permission, owner, group, file size etc.
syntax:
        ls -li <file_name>

iii] Removing link just reduce the link count, but doesn't affect other links
iv] deleteing original file will not affect other links.

2. soft link: (it is a pointer to the original file)
i] these links contains the path for original file.
syntax:  
     ln -s <original-file> <link-name>
eg:
     ln -s demo softlink

ii] soft link is assigened different inode number than original file.
iv] deleting original file the soft link becomes dangling link which points to the non existing file.

